      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Council Rates Clearance and Settlement Adjustments When Selling in Queensland
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        The financial mechanics of a Queensland settlement are more involved than most sellers expect. Here is what rates clearance means, how settlement adjustments work, and what to check before the day.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Settlement day is when ownership of your property transfers to the buyer and the purchase price lands in your account. But before any of that happens, your solicitor and the buyer's solicitor need to agree on a set of financial adjustments that determine exactly how much money changes hands. Rates clearance and settlement adjustments are a routine part of every Queensland property sale, but sellers who do not understand them often end up surprised by the numbers in the settlement statement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a rates clearance certificate is</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, council rates are a charge on the land, not just a personal debt of the property owner. This means that unpaid rates attach to the property and transfer to the new owner if they are not cleared before settlement. A rates clearance certificate is a document issued by the local council (Brisbane City Council, Moreton Bay Regional Council, or whichever council covers your property) that confirms all outstanding rates have been paid to the settlement date.</p>

      <p>The buyer's solicitor will require a rates clearance before allowing settlement to proceed. If there are outstanding rates, settlement will not complete until they are paid. Your solicitor or conveyancer organises this certificate as part of the pre-settlement process, typically in the week before settlement. There is usually a small administrative fee from the council, which varies by council area.</p>

      <p>As a seller, your responsibility is straightforward: make sure your rates are up to date before you approach settlement. Rate arrears that emerge in the final week before settlement can cause delays, and delays can trigger penalties under your contract. If you have been slow with rates payments during the campaign, check your account before you get to that final week.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How settlement adjustments work</h2>
      <p>Rates, water charges, and body corporate levies are charged in advance or in arrears over set periods. Settlement almost never falls exactly at the start or end of one of these billing periods, which means both the buyer and seller are entitled to pay only for the period during which they own the property. Settlement adjustments are the mechanism that achieves this fair split.</p>

      <p>Here is a simple example. Your Brisbane City Council rates are charged quarterly. You paid the current quarter's rates in full at the start of the quarter, covering a full 90-day period. Settlement falls 30 days into that quarter, meaning you have prepaid 60 days of rates that will apply while the buyer owns the property. At settlement, the buyer reimburses you for those 60 days of prepaid rates. This credit appears on your settlement statement.</p>

      <p>The reverse applies if rates are in arrears. If rates for the current period have not yet been paid and settlement falls mid-period, the seller's share of the unpaid amount is deducted from the sale proceeds at settlement, and the buyer's solicitor pays it to council on the buyer's behalf after settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The four main adjustments at a Queensland settlement</h2>
      <p><strong>Council rates</strong> are the general and special rates levied by the local council. These are adjusted to the settlement date. Brisbane City Council issues rates quarterly; regional councils may have different billing cycles. The adjustment is calculated based on the daily rate for the billing period.</p>

      <p><strong>Water and sewerage rates</strong> are levied separately from council general rates and charged by the local water authority (Urban Utilities in inner Brisbane, Unitywater in other areas). Water charges are also adjusted to the settlement date. Note that water consumption charges (the usage portion) are typically handled differently from fixed charges: the final meter reading is taken at or near settlement, and the actual consumption bill is settled separately.</p>

      <p><strong>Body corporate levies</strong> apply if your property is a unit, townhouse, or apartment in a community title scheme. The body corporate levy covers the scheme's insurance, building maintenance, and administration costs. Levies are typically paid quarterly in advance. If you have paid the current quarter's levy and settlement falls mid-quarter, the buyer reimburses you for the unused portion, exactly as with council rates.</p>

      <p><strong>Land tax</strong> is handled slightly differently from the other charges. If land tax applies to your property (typically investment properties and second properties, not owner-occupied homes covered by the principal place of residence exemption), a separate land tax clearance certificate is required from the Queensland Revenue Office. This confirms that land tax has been paid and is not outstanding as a charge on the property.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should do before settlement</h2>
      <p>The most important pre-settlement action is to ensure all rates are current. Arrears will be deducted from your proceeds at settlement, and surprises on settlement day are stressful for everyone involved. Log into your council portal and check your rates balance in the week before settlement. Do the same for your water account.</p>

      <p>If your property is in a body corporate scheme, confirm with the body corporate manager that your levies are up to date. Arrears on body corporate levies are also a charge on the property and will be cleared from your proceeds at settlement.</p>

      <p>Your solicitor will prepare a settlement statement in the day before settlement. This document sets out every financial adjustment and calculates the final balance payable by the buyer. Review it with your solicitor as soon as it is available. If any figures look incorrect, raise them with your solicitor immediately, as settlement statements are sometimes revised right up to the morning of settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why sellers are sometimes surprised by the settlement amount</h2>
      <p>The figure in your settlement statement is rarely exactly the sale price minus your mortgage. The adjustments described above, plus your agent's commission, your solicitor's fees, the discharge fee for your mortgage (if you have one), and any other charges that fall on the seller side of the ledger, all reduce the net proceeds you receive.</p>

      <p>A good solicitor will give you an estimate of your expected net proceeds well before settlement day, so you can plan accordingly. If you have not received one and settlement is approaching, ask for it. Arriving at settlement expecting a specific number and receiving something different, even by a few thousand dollars, creates unnecessary stress at what is already a logistically intense day.</p>

